{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17656492","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17656492"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:14:17+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:14:17+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18745"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18745","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18745"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11477"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77304"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11477","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11477"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18745"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62811"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4932"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10155"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26565"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26571"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77304","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77304"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe epidermis of thick skin contains five distinct layers, including a unique layer not found in thin skin.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the stratum lucideum?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Clear layer between stratum granulosum and stratum corneum","Layer of actively dividing cells","Layer containing keratohyalin granules","Basal layer containing melanocytes","Outermost layer of dead cells"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eclear layer between stratum granulosum and stratum corneum\u003C/strong\u003E correctly describes the stratum lucideum. This thin, translucent layer is found only in thick skin of the palms and soles, positioned between the stratum granulosum and stratum corneum. It contains flattened, dead keratinocytes filled with eleidin, which gives it its characteristic clear appearance under microscopy.\u003C/p\u003E    \u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBasal layer containing melanocytes\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes the stratum basale, the deepest epidermal layer\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELayer containing keratohyalin granules\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes the stratum granulosum, which lies below the stratum lucideum\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOutermost layer of dead cells\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes the stratum corneum, which is the most superficial layer\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELayer of actively dividing cells\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes the stratum basale, where cell division occurs\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe stratum lucideum serves as a transitional zone where keratohyalin is converted to eleidin during the final stages of keratinocyte differentiation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The stratum lucideum is a thin, translucent layer of dead keratinocytes found only in thick skin of palms and soles.","The stratum lucideum contains eleidin, an intermediate form between keratohyalin and keratin.","The stratum lucideum appears clear under microscopy due to the transformation of keratohyalin into eleidin."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevi